* Strengths
- Allows the operators to use commodity hardware preventing vendor lock in. This will further increase
  competition and inturn foster innovation. This is very important for new network operators that don't
  want to shell out big money. 

* Weaknesses
- All of these are very slight nitpicking
- I felt like they could have explained their hypothesis better. I initially thought they were introducing some
  alternative to RANs itself. But then as the paper went on, I realized that they were introducing a new network core.
  But if a company already operates a network then I am perplexed about how magma reduces their cost? Because they have to
  get the RAN in both cases. And if they already have a network core then they just need to wire it up.

- What if having a clean state everytime is beneficial? We just saw in
  the SCION paper that having to adhere to past standards can hold
  back innovation. The fact that 3GPP can wipe the slate clean and
  start over for each generation could be not as bad.  There is also
  an arguement to be made that there isn't much progress during a
  generation as the components cannot be changed. Whereas in Magma our
  innovation is limited by how much software we develop. So there
  could be practically infinite innovation.

  


* Summary

** Introduction
- The reason of people not having Internet is that they are in situations where it doesn't make financial sense
  to provide services. We have to lower the expense of operating a network in these areas.

- Wifi doesn't scale up. Cellular stations don't scale down.
  
- The fundamental problem with existing network core is that the choice of the RAN influences our network stack

- This is different from Computer networks as our stack doesn't change if we switch from WiFi to Ethernet. Infact the above layers
  don't care if it is from WiFi or the Ethernet. This is missing in cellular networks


** Magma Architecture
The key componets of Magma are:
- Some sort of radio access
- Access Gateway
- Orchestrator


The key idea of Magma is to create a wrapper of some sort where you don't have to worry about RAN specific calls
This is analogous to Java where you target your program to the JVM and there is a well defined API for you to do that
The underlying VM takes care of translating it to the appropriate host machine. 


Magma uses a heirarchical SDN architecture to scale even with a centralized point of control



